üî• Stay consistent 


1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Kubernetes (K8s)?
Kubernetes is a container orchestration platform used to run, scale, and manage applications.
It automates deployments, networking, load balancing, and health monitoring.

2Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Pod?
A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes.
It runs one or more containers with shared network and storage.

3Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Spec in Kubernetes?
spec is the part of a YAML file that defines the desired state of an object.
It includes containers, images, volumes, ports, replicas, and resource limits.

4Ô∏è‚É£ What are Labels in Kubernetes?
Labels are key-value pairs used for grouping, filtering, and selecting Kubernetes objects.
Services and Deployments use labels to find the right Pods.

5Ô∏è‚É£ What are Annotations in Kubernetes?
Annotations store non-searchable metadata about an object.
They are used for documentation, automation tools, and tracking information.

6Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Kubernetes Service?
A Service exposes Pods using a stable IP or DNS to allow communication.
Types include ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer, ExternalName, and Headless.

7Ô∏è‚É£ What is Resource Utilization?
Resource utilization means how much CPU, Memory, and storage a Pod/container consumes.
You manage it using resource limits, requests, HPA, and autoscaling.

8Ô∏è‚É£ What is Terraform?
Terraform is an Infrastructure as Code tool used to build, manage, and automate cloud resources.
It uses configuration files to create consistent and repeatable infrastructure.

9Ô∏è‚É£ What is terraform.tfstate?
terraform.tfstate stores Terraform‚Äôs real-time record of deployed resources.
It helps Terraform understand what exists and what needs to be updated.

üîü What is Access Control in Kubernetes?
Kubernetes access is managed using RBAC (Role-Based Access Control).
In cloud platforms like AWS, IAM roles work together with RBAC for secure access.
===============


1Ô∏è‚É£ Kubernetes = Container Orchestration
Manages Pods, scaling, networking.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Pod = Smallest Unit
Runs one or more containers.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Spec = Desired State
Tells Kubernetes what to create.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Labels = Filters
Used for selection & grouping.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Annotations = Extra Info
Metadata not used for selection.

6Ô∏è‚É£ K8s Resources = Objects
Pods, Deployments, Services, ConfigMaps, etc.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Service = Stable Access
ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Resource Utilization = CPU/MEM
Managed using limits, requests, autoscaling.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Terraform.tfstate = Actual State
Terraform checks real vs desired infra.

üîü AWS Access in K8s = IAM + RBAC
AWS controls access using IAM; Kubernetes uses RBAC.
